cupulate interspace|This refers to the phenotype of the is gene in the Zea race Coroico.  This phenotype is not known to be in Zea mays mays, but is found in teosintes.   Galinate writes in MNL 64:  The interspace (is) factor exposes a bare face of rachis between the apex (upper lip) of the cupule and the glume cushion of the diverging spikelet(s) above. Botanically, the interspace represents the backside of the internode from the alternate rachis segment (phytomer). When condensation is sufficiently low for the length of the interspace to become equal to the length of the cupule below, then there is enough extra space to interlock the pedicellate member from an adjacent pair while the sessile member stays in line with its cupule row. The result is a 50% reduction in the kernel-row number.

fused leaves|This is the phenoptype of the mutant "fused leaves" (fdl).  This phenotype is recognizable shortly after germination. In comparison to wild-type siblings, homozygous fdl seedlings show a delay in germination; they also exhibit curly initial leaves that develop precociously while still enclosed in the coleoptile. Frequently, among mutant seedlings, fusion of the leaf surface is also observed: the first and the second leaves or, alternatively, the coleoptile and the first leaf are fused together. Later on in the development, the plant acquires a normal phenotype with expanded and discrete leaves. Homozygous mutant plants at four leaves stage are indistinguishable from wild type plants; they can be grown to maturity and selfed to obtain homozygous progeny seedlings.  Franscarolo, 1998

descriptions: High-haploid|One type of haploid induction is gynogenesis, which is defined as the ability to produce an embryo originating exclusively from the female parent. Pollen triggers the development of the egg cell into an embryo but makes no genetic contribution to the embryo. This is the method apparently utilized by Stock 6 and derivatives.  The other type of haploid induction is androgenesis, in which the embryo contains only paternal chromosomes due to the failure of the egg nucleus to participate in fertilization.  Androgenesis occurs when ig1/ig1 plants are used as the female parent.

naked endosperm|Mutants show variable defects in the aleurone. Strong expression leads to a complete absence of aleurone and a floury-opaque endosperm. Weak expression causes a rough-textured aleurone while intermediate expression causes mosaicism. In section, surface cells of unpigmented kernels are irregular in form and devoid of the dense cytoplasm typical of aleurone cells. No starch grains were evident in the surface cells suggesting that the cells had not switched fate to starchy endosperm.

viviparous kernel|Molecularly characterized mutants are blocked in the biosynthesis of abscisic acid (ABA), or in ABA signaling.  Viviparous mutants often have other phenotypes, notably colorless aleurone from suppression of anthocyanins (vp1) and white endosperm , from blocks in carotenoid synthesis (lw2, vp5, ps1/vp7). Viviparous mutants in maize may be kernel lethal , or if rescued prior to ear desiccation, either viable, or seedling lethal.  Viable mutants are known for vp1, which encodes a transcription factor involved in ABA signaling, and vp14, which encodes an NCED enzyme that cleaves carotenoids to provide xanthoxin, an ABA  precursor.  Seedling lethal mutants include vp5, ps1/vp7 and vp9 , which block production of carotenoid precursors for ABA synthesis ; vp10 and vp15, both deficient in synthesis of the molybdenum cofactor(MoCo) required for ABA synthesis and other pathways. (Apr 2013 last update)

Seedling lethal mutants include vp5, ps1/vp7 and vp9 , which block production of carotenoid precursors for ABA synthesis ; vp10 and vp15, both deficient in synthesis of the molybdenum cofactor(MoCo) required for ABA synthesis and other pathways. (Apr 2013 last update)
